sation. &#10;Muddling up welfare and education has been disastrous I agree.&#10;My LA officer has said to my face, there is no money for training and I have no experience of home education, it is up to you to help me learn. &#10;Why, should I let a plumber into my house who knows nothing about pipes and taps and soldering and accept that I have to teach him, I don't think so. &#10;The LA have all the power they need when problems come to their notice, unfortunately they don't really understand the law and the limits of their responsibilities as the social worker did not in this case. She abandoned the case because the family had been see by and education worker not realising that he was not assessing welfare. It such a person (and he was just one man with an impossible case load) is given more power it will muddy the waters of where the responsibility lies even more and put more children in danger. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1195" language="en" documentId="1149" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="maire52" date="29 July 2010 12:54pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6880753" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="5" thumbsDown="0" origId="1149" notes="" title="Home education: precious, not dangerous"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="91"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="92" end="162"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="163" end="307"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="308" end="370"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="371" end="515"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="516" end="666"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="667" end="1195"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63"/></xmi:XMI>